## Architecture Design

The DevOps pipeline is designed using a modular architecture where each component performs a specific function within the software delivery lifecycle.

The architecture separates responsibilities into multiple layers:

### Source Control Layer
GitHub acts as the central version control system where developers store and manage application source code.

### Continuous Integration Layer
Jenkins orchestrates the CI/CD pipeline and automates the software build, testing, and packaging process.

### Code Quality Layer
SonarQube analyzes application source code to detect vulnerabilities, bugs, and maintainability issues before deployment.

### Containerization Layer
Docker packages the application into a container image, ensuring consistent runtime environments across development, testing, and production systems.

### Security Layer
Trivy performs vulnerability scanning on container images to detect known security flaws before the application is deployed.

### Container Registry Layer
DockerHub stores container images and acts as the artifact repository for the deployment stage.

### GitOps Deployment Layer
Argo CD monitors the DevOps repository and automatically synchronizes Kubernetes deployments based on the desired configuration stored in Git.

### Container Orchestration Layer
Kubernetes manages containerized workloads, handles scaling, load balancing, and ensures application availability.

### Notification Layer
Slack integration allows teams to receive real-time notifications about build status and deployment outcomes.
